---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FlavorTabs from "../../../components/FlavorTabs.astro";
import ModuleHero from "../../../components/module/ModuleHero.astro";
import ModuleScenario from "../../../components/module/ModuleScenario.astro";
import ModuleFlowDiagram from "../../../components/module/ModuleFlowDiagram.astro";
import TraceWaterfallDemo from "../../../components/module/demos/TraceWaterfallDemo.astro";
import ModuleFooterNav from "../../../components/module/ModuleFooterNav.astro";
import ModuleRecap from "../../../components/module/ModuleRecap.astro";
import { flavor as gcp } from "../../../data/flavors/gcp";
import { flavor as aws } from "../../../data/flavors/aws";
import { flavor as azure } from "../../../data/flavors/azure";
import { flavor as oss } from "../../../data/flavors/oss";

const moduleId = "55-observability";
const entries = {
  gcp: gcp[moduleId],
  aws: aws[moduleId],
  azure: azure[moduleId],
  oss: oss[moduleId],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="55 · Observability for LLMs">
  <article>
    <ModuleHero moduleId={moduleId}>
      <p>
        Module 45 told you your pipeline is good on average, on a golden set you built ahead of time. Observability
        answers the harder question: what happened on <em>this specific request</em>, right now, in production — and
        it builds the event log every later module (evaluation regressions, security audits, cost analysis) ends up
        reading from.
      </p>
    </ModuleHero>

    <ModuleScenario moduleId={moduleId} />

    <ModuleFlowDiagram moduleId={moduleId} />

    <h2>Traces and spans for RAG</h2>
    <p>
      A single user question touches four stages: embed the query, retrieve chunks, assemble the prompt, and call the
      model. Logging each stage separately makes it nearly impossible to reconstruct what happened for one request.
      Instead, wrap the whole request in one <strong>trace</strong>, with each stage as a nested <strong>span</strong>.
      When a user reports a bad answer, you open one trace and see exactly which stage went wrong — instead of
      grepping four different logs and hoping the timestamps line up.
    </p>

    <TraceWaterfallDemo />

    <h2>Token accounting per request</h2>
    <p>
      Attach input, output, and cached token counts as attributes on the generation span, per request. This looks like
      overkill until Module 75, where the FinOps unit-economics work is a straight SQL join against this exact data —
      without it, cost analysis degenerates into "the monthly bill went up, no idea why."
    </p>

    <h2>Latency budgets: TTFT vs. total latency</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Time-to-first-token (TTFT)</strong> is how long a user waits before anything appears — the number that
      determines whether a streaming response feels instant or sluggish. <strong>Total latency</strong> is how long
      the full answer takes. A model can have great TTFT and mediocre total latency (streaming hides it) or the
      reverse. Track both, and budget them separately: a chat UI cares more about TTFT, a batch job cares only about
      total latency.
    </p>

    <h2>The event log as the analytical backbone</h2>
    <p>
      Once every request is a trace with token counts, latency, and outcome, that trace store stops being "just logs"
      and becomes the platform's central table. Module 45's regression evals can sample real production traffic from
      it. Module 65's security review can search it for suspicious patterns. Module 75's cost analysis joins directly
      against it. Instrumenting this once, well, here is what makes the rest of the advanced curriculum possible
      without re-plumbing logging every time.
    </p>

    <h2>Try it in your flavor</h2>
    <FlavorTabs moduleId={moduleId} entries={entries} />

    <h2>Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Logging only the final response text — you lose the ability to tell whether retrieval or generation caused a bad answer.</li>
      <li>Skipping token-count attributes because "we'll add cost tracking later" — Module 75 needs this data from day one, not retroactively.</li>
      <li>Optimizing only for total latency and ignoring TTFT, which is what users actually perceive as "slow" in a streaming UI.</li>
      <li>Treating traces as a debugging-only tool instead of the shared data source that evaluation, security, and cost modules all depend on.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
  <ModuleRecap moduleId={moduleId} />
  <ModuleFooterNav moduleId={moduleId} />
</BaseLayout>
